<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1925-02-28T13:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1925-02-28T13:00:00-05:00" n="516" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d516">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">819.00/1158: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Minister in Panama</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">South</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to
                                the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Panama</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1925-02-28T13:00:00-05:00"><hi rend="italic">February 28,
                                        1925—1 p.m.</hi></date><lb/>[Received 4:50
                            p.m.]</dateline></opener>
                        <p>26. The Minister for Foreign Affairs assures me Indians will not be
                            attacked unless they renew hostilities. Seizure of boats a precautionary
                            measure which can be abandoned if it causes difficulties.</p>
                        <p>Señor Alfaro believes that public opinion will demand thorough
                            investigation of Marsh’s activities but it is disposed to give him
                            benefit of all favorable evidence. Justice of the Supreme Court leaving
                            tonight for Carti to make this investigation and hear evidence of
                            Indians.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">South</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>